The paper deals with binary sequences that have applications in cryptography and communications, which are topics covered by several sub-categories in computer science. However, the focus on autocorrelation and linear complexity suggests that the paper is more likely to belong to the Information Theory (cs.IT) or Cryptography and Security (cs.CR) sub-categories. The use of sequence polynomial approach also suggests that the paper may belong to the Data Structures (cs.DS) or Signal and Image Processing (cs.SI) sub-categories. Finally, the fact that the paper deals with sequences suggests that it may also belong to the Networking and Internet Architecture (cs.NI) sub-category.
